{"title_page": "1949 Central Queensland cyclone", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\nThe '''1949 Central Queensland cyclone''' was an unnamed [[tropical cyclone]] that struck the [[Central Queensland]] coast in [[Australia]] on 2 March 1949.<ref>[http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/eastern.shtml Previous Cyclones: Historical Impacts Along The East Coast], [[Bureau of Meteorology]], [[Australian Government]]. Accessed 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe cyclone impacted the cities of [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]] and [[Rockhampton]] and their surrounding towns and localities.<ref name=rocky>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178873 Rockhampton battered by 100mph cyclone; Two killed, damage throughout city], ''[[The Central Queensland Herald]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref name=gladstone>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178764 \u00a3150,000 damage at Gladstone], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179163 Cyclone losses in Country], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  There were a number of fatalities, and extensive damage was sustained to many homes and businesses and much of the local infrastructure, including the telecommunications, electricity and transport networks.<ref name=cyclonefury>(2 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216476842 Cyclone fury strikes - Gladstone heavily hit, buildings wrecked, others damaged], ''[[The Telegraph (Brisbane)|The Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18105610 Town battered by cyclone: Four killed, many homeless], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Bureau of Meteorology]] lists the 1949 Central Queensland cyclone as one of the 15 major cyclones to strike the east coast of [[Queensland]] between 1890 and 2006.<ref>[http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/about/cyclones-eastern.shtml#climatology Climatology: Cyclone frequency], Bureau of Meteorology, Australian Government. Accessed 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Formation==\nOn 28 February 1949, reports emerged that a tropical cyclone had developed and was 100 miles east-south-east of [[Willis Island]], moving in a south-south-westerly direction.<ref>(28 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216509627 Weather Chart], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  On 1 March 1949, it was reported the cyclone had been maintaining a [[Fermat's spiral|parabolic]] south-westerly to southerly track, and was 80 miles east of [[Cape Capricorn]].<ref>(1 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216477945 Weather Chart], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  By 2 March 1949, the cyclone had travelled further south to between [[Bundaberg]] and Gladstone, where the system deepened and crossed the coast just south of Gladstone.<ref>(2 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216476927 Weather Chart], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49932238 Weather], ''[[The Courier-Mail]]''. Retrieved 11 December 1949.</ref>\n\nThe cyclone then almost immediately swung north, and travelled back up the coast to Rockhampton before eventually moving west through [[Capricornia, Queensland|Capricornia]] dumping heavy amounts of rain throughout inland areas and ultimately weakening near [[Tambo, Queensland|Tambo]].<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49925404 Cyclone moves west fast; Gladstone starts to rebuild homes, Rockhampton desolation], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896478/5484321 The cyclone travelled this way (Cyclone tracking map)], ''[[The Morning Bulletin]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe 1949 Central Queensland cyclone was the third to cross the coast in the space of three weeks. It followed the unnamed 1949 [[Far North Queensland]] cyclone which caused widespread damage to [[Cooktown]] on 10 February 1949.<ref>(12 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/42614847/3082406 Cooktown devastated but no loss of life: only eight residences survive battering by cyclone], ''Cairns Post''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(13 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/42614710 Cooktown suffers great cyclone damage: Many premises in main street blown down], ''Cairns Post''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(15 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/42615120/3082422 Graphic pen-picture of ruined Cooktown], ''Cairns Post''. Retrieved 8 December 2018.</ref> A weaker cyclone then crossed the coast north of [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]] on 16 February 1949, bringing heavy rain to the city but no significant damage.<ref>(17 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/171107005 Cyclonic rain floods city], ''The Daily Mercury''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(17 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49920228 Coast misses bad damage - cyclone rushes out to sea], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n===Gladstone===\nGladstone was extensively damaged when the cyclone hit.<ref name=cyclonefury/><ref name=razed>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/117085749 Four cyclone victims: Gladstone was almost razed, many homeless], ''Queensland Times''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nWinds were estimated to have gusted up to 120 miles per hour as the cyclone passed over Gladstone, with the peak estimated to have occurred at around 1pm in the afternoon.<ref name=razed/>\n\nSixty homes in Gladstone were unroofed, and dozens of other buildings were damaged. The [[Roman Catholic Church]]'s [[convent school]] and the [[Presbyterian Church]] were destroyed, while the Queen's Hotel and the [[Church of England]] were unroofed and the Gladstone [[Slaughterhouse|meatworks]] badly damaged.<ref name=gladstone/>  School children were taken out of the convent school building two hours before it was demolished.<ref name=cyclonefury/>\n\nWhen the police station was unroofed, a local police sergeant was forced to move his family into the local watchhouse until that too was badly damaged, forcing the family to seek shelter in the court house.<ref name=razed/>\n\nMany [[marine vessel]]s were destroyed or badly damaged including a local tourist boat ''Norwest'' which was washed up onto the banks of Auckland Creek.<ref name=cyclonefury/>\n\nGladstone's communication and electricity network was badly damaged in the cyclone.<ref name=nightofterror>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49932098 Night of Terror in Cyclone - Four deaths; big loss in Rockhampton, Gladstone], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThere was substantial crop losses in the surrounding area including pawpaw crops in the [[Yarwun, Queensland|Yarwun]]-[[Targinnie]] district and peanut crops in the [[Mount Larcom]] district.<ref>(9 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896698/5484340 Pawpaw loss said to be \u00a3100,000], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDue to the cyclone, a [[train#passenger trains|passenger train]] carrying 350 passengers was held at [[Raglan, Queensland|Raglan]], between Gladstone and Rockhampton, for 26 hours. During the stopover, groups of passengers had to regularly walk to the local store and hotel to for food supplies. As floodwaters in Raglan Creek rose nearby, the passengers and crew assisted the hotelkeeper at Raglan to move furniture to higher ground.<ref>(6 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/231068129 Flood victims eat out town], ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring the extensive clean up, the Gladstone mayor criticised the condition of 30 tons of roofing iron which had been sent to Gladstone for cyclone repairs, describing the iron as \"rusted and useless\" as it had been exposed to the elements on inadequately-covered railway wagons.<ref>(8 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216473383 Roofing useless], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===Rockhampton===\nThe city of Rockhampton and adjacent coastal areas were extensively damaged when the cyclone made an unexpected northern turn back up the coast, once it had crossed near Gladstone.<ref name=battered>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896260/5484302 Rockhampton battered by 100mph cyclone - two killed, damage throughout city], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe estimated peak of the cyclone in Rockhampton was estimated to have been at 7pm when winds of up to 100 miles per hour were recorded, and the barometric pressure reached 28.56 inches of mercury (967 hectopascals) - the lowest to ever have been recorded in Rockhampton.<ref name=rocky/>\n\nMany homes, businesses and landmarks in Rockhampton suffered substantial damage.<ref name=rocky/>\n\nExtensive damage was reported at the [[Rockhampton railway station]] where approximately 100 sheet of iron was dislodged above the railway platforms.<ref name=battered/> After being severed during the cyclone, the [[Yeppoon railway line|rail link between Rockhampton and Yeppoon]] was closed until repairs could be made to the damaged tracks.<ref name=yeppoonrail>(12 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897087 Yeppoon rail link restored], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Other parts of the local railway network to have been damaged during the cyclone included the line to [[Ridgelands, Queensland|Ridgelands]], [[Dawson Valley (Theodore) railway line|the line from Baralaba to Theodore]], and [[Callide Valley railway line|the line from Rannes to Thangool]].<ref name=yeppoonrail/>\n \nThere was an estimated \u00a320,000 done to the Wintergarden Theatre while the picture theatre at [[Koongal]] was also extensively damaged.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896254/5484302 City Theatre Hard Hit], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(21 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897971 Volunteers re-erecting Koongal picture theatre], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Rockhampton Botanic Gardens]] sustained damage.<ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896414/5484317 Damage at Botanic Gardens], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDamage to the electricity network was extensive with flying iron and trees cutting down main power lines.<ref name=repair>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896362/5484307 Repair men at work], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Power supply began being progressively restored the day following the cyclone, with priority given to hospitals, water treatment plants and other essential services.<ref name=repair/>  With widespread power outages, volunteers were called for to manually operate an [[iron lung]] for a 16-year-old patient at [[Rockhampton Base Hospital|Rockhampton General Hospital]] until power was restored.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216474537 \"Pumpers\" saved life of iron lung inmate], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  The lack of auxiliary power at the hospital and the necessity of requiring volunteers to manually operate the machine prompted a public debate in the local press.<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896879/5484349 Correspondence: The Iron Lung], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(11 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896938 Correspondence: The Iron Lung], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(24 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56898363 The Iron Lung], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nCommunities along the [[Capricorn Coast]], including [[Yeppoon]] and [[Emu Park]], also sustained extensive damage during the cyclone.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896333/5484307 Seaside towns took heavy blows], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896437/5484317 Yeppoon battered for 22 hours], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Dead cattle began washing up on the beaches along [[Zilzie]] and Emu Park after the cyclone. Mass burials of the beasts took place at the end of each beach.<ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896380/5484314 Cattle among casualties], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDamage was also sustained at [[Port Alma]] and the Rockhampton Harbour.<ref>(16 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897538 Cyclone died 1900 damage to local ports], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe mining town of [[Mount Morgan, Queensland|Mount Morgan]], south-west of Rockhampton, experienced strong winds and heavy rain, but the damage to the town was minimal compared to Rockhampton although some roofs were blown off buildings and some [[veranda]]s were damaged, including at the Avoca Hotel and Allen's Hotel at Tipperary Point.<ref name=mtmorgan>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896334 Night of terror at Mt Morgan], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nMany [[crop]]s in the area were lost, including a substantial [[citrus]] crop from [[Byfield, Queensland|Byfield]].<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179063 Byfield loses citrus crop in cyclone], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n[[Kalapa, Queensland|Kalapa]] also felt the effects of the cyclone as it moved inland.<ref>(7 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896571/5484327 Kalapa's cyclone experience], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> Further west, strong winds and heavy rain were recorded at [[Emerald, Queensland|Emerald]] and throughout the Central Highlands but no substantial damage was reported.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896358/5484307 Heavy wind at Emerald], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe publication of Rockhampton's [[daily newspaper]] was abandoned during the cyclone, and therefore there was no edition of ''The Morning Bulletin'' issued on 3 March 1949.<ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/page/6167520 Morning Bulletin (Rockhampton, Qld: 1878-1954) Issue Missing: 1949-03-03], National Library of Australia. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> The Rockhampton Newspaper Co Pty Ltd issued an apology in the following day's edition, explaining that the decision not to publish had been owing to \"unsurmountable difficulties\".<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896276/5484302 No \"Bulletin\" Yesterday], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nLocal radio station [[4RK]] remained on air during the cyclone but staff were forced to cover transmitting equipment with tents and had to tear up linoleum from the floor so it could be used to cover the generator when water began pouring through the roof.<ref>(7 April 1952) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/57097018 New equipment at 4RK], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDespite the widespread damage and the substantial clean up that occurred following the cyclone, several scheduled events went ahead as planned in the weeks following, including the visit to Rockhampton by [[Lord Rowallan]], the [[Chief Scout (The Scout Association)|Chief Scout]] of the [[Boy Scout Association]], who attended several official events in the city, including a civic reception at [[Rockhampton Town Hall|City Hall]] and a [[Rotary Club]] luncheon.<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178980 Visit of Lord Rowallan], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Communist Party of Australia]] also attempted to proceed with a scheduled open-air meeting in the city centre on 28 March 1949, which led to the infamous 1949 Rockhampton riot when around 1500 protestors gate-crashed the meeting and showered supporters with various projectiles including rotten eggs, rotten fruit, [[flour bomb]]s and [[stink bomb]]s before breaking through police cordons and assaulting party supporters.<ref>(29 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18108831 Stink bombs hurled at Communists], ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(29 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/205364757 Communists mobbed in Rockhampton], ''[[The Age]]''. Retrieved 8 December 2018.</ref><ref>(29 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56898821 Angry scenes at street meeting], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(30 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56899008/5484498 Communists cancel Mt Morgan meeting], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===Bundaberg/Maryborough===\nThe cyclone's wind was not felt further south in centres such as Bundaberg and Maryborough, although some trees were uprooted, and some homes damaged, including one in East Bundaberg where a young boy was killed when a tree fell on a family home. Several vessels damaged at [[Hervey Bay]] due to rough seas.<ref name=cyclonefury/>  Damage was also reported at [[Burnett Heads]].<ref name=cyclonefury/>  Flooding occurred in these areas brought about by the heavy rain associated with the cyclone.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896891 Bundaberg flooding], ''Queensland Times''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n===Fatalities during cyclone===\n*'''John Fontaine''' - a 45-year-old man killed when he was blown from the roof of a Rockhampton property<ref name=nightofterror/>\n*'''Charles William Inslay James''' - a 56-year-old man killed when hit by a falling tree branch in Rockhampton<ref>(26 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56898632 OBITUARY: Mr. W. I. James], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n*'''Alfred Edward Ramett''' - a four-year-old boy killed when a tree fell through his home in Bundaberg<ref name=nightofterror/>\n*'''Jacob Worthington''' - a 68-year-old man killed when he was blown from the roof of a Gladstone property<ref name=nightofterror/>\n\n===Fatalities after cyclone===\n*'''George Coulson''' - a man killed when he likely fell from his horse and drowned while attempting to cross a creek near [[Jambin, Queensland|Jambin]].<ref>(12 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897111 Flood story from Jambin - Farmer Drowned], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n*'''Dennis James Hannifen''' - a 29-year-old man who was killed when he fell from his horse and drowned while attempting to cross Little Gin Creek near [[Longreach]].<ref name=twodrowned>(15 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897405 Two drowned in flooded creeks], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n*'''Frank Hobson''' - a 15-year-old boy who drowned at Mount Morgan Company's upper dam while fishing with his brother.<ref>(24 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179486 Boy drowned at Mt Morgan], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> The dam along with the [[Dee River (Queensland)|Dee River]] both flooded during the cyclone.<ref name=mtmorgan/>\n*'''John Warry''' - a man killed when he fell from his horse and drowned while attempting to drive cattle across Callide Creek near [[Goovigen]].<ref name=twodrowned/>\n\n===Injuries===\nMany non-fatal injuries were reported during the cyclone.<ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178757 Cyclone victims and casualties], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Many rescues also took place during and following the cyclone.<ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49932101 Ordeal of city in blackout], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> A family of seven was rescued by police after sheltering under their demolished house at Gavial Siding for two days without food.<ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896404/5484314 Rescue job by police], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Relief Fundraising==\nThe Rockhampton Cyclone Relief Fund was established soon after the cyclone, to assist victims in the [[City of Rockhampton]], [[Livingstone Shire]] and [[Fitzroy Shire]] areas.<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179152 Committees set up for relief of distress], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  By 8 June 1949, a total of \u00a33162 had been raised for the fund.<ref name=end>(9 June 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56906755 End cyclone relief payments in fortnight, says mayor], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>   A total of 79 applications totalling of \u00a31466/5/10 in assistance had been authorised while another 225 applications from the relief fund were under consideration.<ref name=end/>\n\nGladstone also had a similar cyclone relief fund.<ref>(19 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/191845596 \u00a3100 gift for cyclone relief funds], ''[[Warwick Daily News]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(26 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/117096654 Forest Hill CWA], ''Queensland Times''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nA variety show was held at the Palais Royal in Rockhampton on 6 April 1949 as a fundraising event, featuring well known Brisbane comedians Buster Fiddes and Mavis Monk.<ref>(6 April 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56899747 Variety show for cyclone relief], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  The show had a disappointing crowd with only 270 people attending the event.<ref>(7 April 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56899875 Cyclone relief benefit], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nFollowing the cyclone, discussions took place regarding how to improve warnings of an approaching cyclone. The Rockhampton Chamber of Commerce criticised the fact that no person in the city had been tasked with the responsibility of warning people of an incoming cyclone.<ref>(22 April 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56901500 Cyclone warning responsibility], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThere were also calls in the press for homes, businesses and public property in northern and central areas of Queensland to be strengthened to better withstand tropical cyclones that crossed the coast into populated areas.<ref>(6 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/98290844 Grim lesson of cyclone: North must build stronger homes], ''[[The Sunday Mail (Brisbane)|The Sunday Mail]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe 1949 Central Queensland cyclone is still remembered by many residents in Rockhampton and Gladstone.<ref>(14 November 2007) [http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2007/10/24/2069363.htm Discover Central Queensland - Ambrose], [[ABC Capricornia]]. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>Spelitis, Helen (6 February 2009) [https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/late-start-to-cyclone-season-not-unusual/2535415 Cyclone season is running late, but may still hit hard - one died in Gladstone as 1949 cyclone hit town], ''[[The Observer (Gladstone)|The Observer]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  However, until [[Cyclone Marcia]] struck Rockhampton in 2015, there had been a growing sense of complacency amongst others who had a misguided belief that the city would never be seriously affected by a cyclone.<ref>McKee, Christine (27 February 2015) [https://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/natures-fury-felt-across-centuries-cyclones-queens/2555313 Nature's fury felt across centuries across Queensland], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Charlie James Memorial Trophy has been awarded to local Rockhampton [[tennis]] players since 1960. It is named after Charles James who was killed during the cyclone.<ref>Kennedy, Alan (6 February 2009) [https://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/cup-serves-up-49th-tourney/164272 Cup serves up 49th tourney], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1949 in Australia]]\n[[Category:1949 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:Central Queensland]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclones in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\nThe '''1949 Central Queensland cyclone''' was an unnamed [[tropical cyclone]] that struck the [[Central Queensland]] coast in [[Australia]] on 2 March 1949.<ref>[http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/eastern.shtml Previous Cyclones: Historical Impacts Along The East Coast], [[Bureau of Meteorology]], [[Australian Government]]. Accessed 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe cyclone impacted the cities of [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]] and [[Rockhampton]] and their surrounding towns and localities.<ref name=rocky>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178873 Rockhampton battered by 100mph cyclone; Two killed, damage throughout city], ''[[The Central Queensland Herald]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref name=gladstone>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178764 \u00a3150,000 damage at Gladstone], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179163 Cyclone losses in Country], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  There were a number of fatalities, and extensive damage was sustained to many homes and businesses and much of the local infrastructure, including the telecommunications, electricity and transport networks.<ref name=cyclonefury>(2 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216476842 Cyclone fury strikes - Gladstone heavily hit, buildings wrecked, others damaged], ''[[The Telegraph (Brisbane)|The Telegraph]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18105610 Town battered by cyclone: Four killed, many homeless], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Bureau of Meteorology]] lists the 1949 Central Queensland cyclone as one of the 15 major cyclones to strike the east coast of [[Queensland]] between 1890 and 2006.<ref>[http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/about/cyclones-eastern.shtml#climatology Climatology: Cyclone frequency], Bureau of Meteorology, Australian Government. Accessed 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Formation==\nOn 28 February 1949, reports emerged that a tropical cyclone had developed and was 100 miles east-south-east of [[Willis Island]], moving in a south-south-westerly direction.<ref>(28 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216509627 Weather Chart], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  On 1 March 1949, it was reported the cyclone had been maintaining a [[Fermat's spiral|parabolic]] south-westerly to southerly track, and was 80 miles east of [[Cape Capricorn]].<ref>(1 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216477945 Weather Chart], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  By 2 March 1949, the cyclone had travelled further south to between [[Bundaberg]] and Gladstone, where the system deepened and crossed the coast just south of Gladstone.<ref>(2 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216476927 Weather Chart], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49932238 Weather], ''[[The Courier-Mail]]''. Retrieved 11 December 1949.</ref>\n\nThe cyclone then almost immediately swung north, and travelled back up the coast to Rockhampton before eventually moving west through [[Capricornia, Queensland|Capricornia]] dumping heavy amounts of rain throughout inland areas and ultimately weakening near [[Tambo, Queensland|Tambo]].<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49925404 Cyclone moves west fast; Gladstone starts to rebuild homes, Rockhampton desolation], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896478/5484321 The cyclone travelled this way (Cyclone tracking map)], ''[[The Morning Bulletin]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe 1949 Central Queensland cyclone was the third to cross the coast in the space of three weeks. It followed the unnamed 1949 [[Far North Queensland]] cyclone which caused widespread damage to [[Cooktown]] on 10 February 1949.<ref>(12 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/42614847/3082406 Cooktown devastated but no loss of life: only eight residences survive battering by cyclone], ''Cairns Post''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(13 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/42614710 Cooktown suffers great cyclone damage: Many premises in main street blown down], ''Cairns Post''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(15 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/42615120/3082422 Graphic pen-picture of ruined Cooktown], ''Cairns Post''. Retrieved 8 December 2018.</ref> A weaker cyclone then crossed the coast north of [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]] on 16 February 1949, bringing heavy rain to the city but no significant damage.<ref>(17 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/171107005 Cyclonic rain floods city], ''The Daily Mercury''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(17 February 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49920228 Coast misses bad damage - cyclone rushes out to sea], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n===Gladstone===\nGladstone was extensively damaged when the cyclone hit.<ref name=cyclonefury/><ref name=razed>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/117085749 Four cyclone victims: Gladstone was almost razed, many homeless], ''Queensland Times''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nWinds were estimated to have gusted up to 120 miles per hour as the cyclone passed over Gladstone, with the peak estimated to have occurred at around 1pm in the afternoon.<ref name=razed/>\n\nSixty homes in Gladstone were unroofed, and dozens of other buildings were damaged. The [[Roman Catholic Church]]'s [[convent school]] and the [[Presbyterian Church]] were destroyed, while the Queen's Hotel and the [[Church of England]] were unroofed and the Gladstone [[Slaughterhouse|meatworks]] badly damaged.<ref name=gladstone/>  School children were taken out of the convent school building two hours before it was demolished.<ref name=cyclonefury/>\n\nWhen the police station was unroofed, a local police sergeant was forced to move his family into the local watchhouse until that too was badly damaged, forcing the family to seek shelter in the court house.<ref name=razed/>\n\nMany [[marine vessel]]s were destroyed or badly damaged including a local tourist boat ''Norwest'' which was washed up onto the banks of Auckland Creek.<ref name=cyclonefury/>\n\nGladstone's communication and electricity network was badly damaged in the cyclone.<ref name=nightofterror>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49932098 Night of Terror in Cyclone - Four deaths; big loss in Rockhampton, Gladstone], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThere was substantial crop losses in the surrounding area including pawpaw crops in the [[Yarwun, Queensland|Yarwun]]-[[Targinnie]] district and peanut crops in the [[Mount Larcom]] district.<ref>(9 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896698/5484340 Pawpaw loss said to be \u00a3100,000], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDue to the cyclone, a [[train#passenger trains|passenger train]] carrying 350 passengers was held at [[Raglan, Queensland|Raglan]], between Gladstone and Rockhampton, for 26 hours. During the stopover, groups of passengers had to regularly walk to the local store and hotel to for food supplies. As floodwaters in Raglan Creek rose nearby, the passengers and crew assisted the hotelkeeper at Raglan to move furniture to higher ground.<ref>(6 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/231068129 Flood victims eat out town], ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring the extensive clean up, the Gladstone mayor criticised the condition of 30 tons of roofing iron which had been sent to Gladstone for cyclone repairs, describing the iron as \"rusted and useless\" as it had been exposed to the elements on inadequately-covered railway wagons.<ref>(8 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216473383 Roofing useless], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===Rockhampton===\nThe city of Rockhampton and adjacent coastal areas were extensively damaged when the cyclone made an unexpected northern turn back up the coast, once it had crossed near Gladstone.<ref name=battered>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896260/5484302 Rockhampton battered by 100mph cyclone - two killed, damage throughout city], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe estimated peak of the cyclone in Rockhampton was estimated to have been at 7pm when winds of up to 100 miles per hour were recorded, and the barometric pressure reached 28.56 inches of mercury (967 hectopascals) - the lowest to ever have been recorded in Rockhampton.<ref name=rocky/>\n\nMany homes, businesses and landmarks in Rockhampton suffered substantial damage.<ref name=rocky/>\n\nExtensive damage was reported at the [[Rockhampton railway station]] where approximately 100 sheet of iron was dislodged above the railway platforms.<ref name=battered/> After being severed during the cyclone, the [[Yeppoon railway line|rail link between Rockhampton and Yeppoon]] was closed until repairs could be made to the damaged tracks.<ref name=yeppoonrail>(12 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897087 Yeppoon rail link restored], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Other parts of the local railway network to have been damaged during the cyclone included the line to [[Ridgelands, Queensland|Ridgelands]], [[Dawson Valley (Theodore) railway line|the line from Baralaba to Theodore]], and [[Callide Valley railway line|the line from Rannes to Thangool]].<ref name=yeppoonrail/>\n \nThere was an estimated \u00a320,000 done to the Wintergarden Theatre while the picture theatre at [[Koongal]] was also extensively damaged.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896254/5484302 City Theatre Hard Hit], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(21 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897971 Volunteers re-erecting Koongal picture theatre], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Rockhampton Botanic Gardens]] sustained damage.<ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896414/5484317 Damage at Botanic Gardens], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDamage to the electricity network was extensive with flying iron and trees cutting down main power lines.<ref name=repair>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896362/5484307 Repair men at work], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Power supply began being progressively restored the day following the cyclone, with priority given to hospitals, water treatment plants and other essential services.<ref name=repair/>  With widespread power outages, volunteers were called for to manually operate an [[iron lung]] for a 16-year-old patient at [[Rockhampton Base Hospital|Rockhampton General Hospital]] until power was restored.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/216474537 \"Pumpers\" saved life of iron lung inmate], ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  The lack of auxiliary power at the hospital and the necessity of requiring volunteers to manually operate the machine prompted a public debate in the local press.<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896879/5484349 Correspondence: The Iron Lung], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(11 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896938 Correspondence: The Iron Lung], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(24 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56898363 The Iron Lung], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nCommunities along the [[Capricorn Coast]], including [[Yeppoon]] and [[Emu Park]], also sustained extensive damage during the cyclone.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896333/5484307 Seaside towns took heavy blows], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896437/5484317 Yeppoon battered for 22 hours], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Dead cattle began washing up on the beaches along [[Zilzie]] and Emu Park after the cyclone. Mass burials of the beasts took place at the end of each beach.<ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896380/5484314 Cattle among casualties], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDamage was also sustained at [[Port Alma]] and the Rockhampton Harbour.<ref>(16 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897538 Cyclone died 1900 damage to local ports], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe mining town of [[Mount Morgan, Queensland|Mount Morgan]], south-west of Rockhampton, experienced strong winds and heavy rain, but the damage to the town was minimal compared to Rockhampton although some roofs were blown off buildings and some [[veranda]]s were damaged, including at the Avoca Hotel and Allen's Hotel at Tipperary Point.<ref name=mtmorgan>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896334 Night of terror at Mt Morgan], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nMany [[crop]]s in the area were lost, including a substantial [[citrus]] crop from [[Byfield, Queensland|Byfield]].<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179063 Byfield loses citrus crop in cyclone], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n[[Kalapa, Queensland|Kalapa]] also felt the effects of the cyclone as it moved inland.<ref>(7 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896571/5484327 Kalapa's cyclone experience], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> Further west, strong winds and heavy rain were recorded at [[Emerald, Queensland|Emerald]] and throughout the Central Highlands but no substantial damage was reported.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896358/5484307 Heavy wind at Emerald], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe publication of Rockhampton's [[daily newspaper]] was abandoned during the cyclone, and therefore there was no edition of ''The Morning Bulletin'' issued on 3 March 1949.<ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/page/6167520 Morning Bulletin (Rockhampton, Qld: 1878-1954) Issue Missing: 1949-03-03], National Library of Australia. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> The Rockhampton Newspaper Co Pty Ltd issued an apology in the following day's edition, explaining that the decision not to publish had been owing to \"unsurmountable difficulties\".<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896276/5484302 No \"Bulletin\" Yesterday], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nLocal radio station [[4RK]] remained on air during the cyclone but staff were forced to cover transmitting equipment with tents and had to tear up linoleum from the floor so it could be used to cover the generator when water began pouring through the roof.<ref>(7 April 1952) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/57097018 New equipment at 4RK], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nDespite the widespread damage and the substantial clean up that occurred following the cyclone, several scheduled events went ahead as planned in the weeks following, including the visit to Rockhampton by [[Lord Rowallan]], the [[Chief Scout (The Scout Association)|Chief Scout]] of the [[Boy Scout Association]], who attended several official events in the city, including a civic reception at [[Rockhampton Town Hall|City Hall]] and a [[Rotary Club]] luncheon.<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178980 Visit of Lord Rowallan], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Communist Party of Australia]] also attempted to proceed with a scheduled open-air meeting in the city centre on 28 March 1949, which led to the infamous 1949 Rockhampton riot when around 1500 protestors gate-crashed the meeting and showered supporters with various projectiles including rotten eggs, rotten fruit, [[flour bomb]]s and [[stink bomb]]s before breaking through police cordons and assaulting party supporters.<ref>(29 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18108831 Stink bombs hurled at Communists], ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(29 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/205364757 Communists mobbed in Rockhampton], ''[[The Age]]''. Retrieved 8 December 2018.</ref><ref>(29 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56898821 Angry scenes at street meeting], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(30 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56899008/5484498 Communists cancel Mt Morgan meeting], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===Bundaberg/Maryborough===\nThe cyclone's wind was not felt further south in centres such as Bundaberg and Maryborough, although some trees were uprooted, and some homes damaged, including one in East Bundaberg where a young boy was killed when a tree fell on a family home. Several vessels damaged at [[Hervey Bay]] due to rough seas.<ref name=cyclonefury/>  Damage was also reported at [[Burnett Heads]].<ref name=cyclonefury/>  Flooding occurred in these areas brought about by the heavy rain associated with the cyclone.<ref>(4 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896891 Bundaberg flooding], ''Queensland Times''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n===Fatalities during cyclone===\n*'''John Fontaine''' - a 45-year-old man killed when he was blown from the roof of a Rockhampton property<ref name=nightofterror/>\n*'''Charles William Inslay James''' - a 56-year-old man killed when hit by a falling tree branch in Rockhampton<ref>(26 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56898632 OBITUARY: Mr. W. I. James], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n*'''Alfred Edward Ramett''' - a four-year-old boy killed when a tree fell through his home in Bundaberg<ref name=nightofterror/>\n*'''Jacob Worthington''' - a 68-year-old man killed when he was blown from the roof of a Gladstone property<ref name=nightofterror/>\n\n===Fatalities after cyclone===\n*'''George Coulson''' - a man killed when he likely fell from his horse and drowned while attempting to cross a creek near [[Jambin, Queensland|Jambin]].<ref>(12 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897111 Flood story from Jambin - Farmer Drowned], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n*'''Dennis James Hannifen''' - a 29-year-old man who was killed when he fell from his horse and drowned while attempting to cross Little Gin Creek near [[Longreach]].<ref name=twodrowned>(15 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56897405 Two drowned in flooded creeks], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n*'''Frank Hobson''' - a 15-year-old boy who drowned at Mount Morgan Company's upper dam while fishing with his brother.<ref>(24 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179486 Boy drowned at Mt Morgan], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> The dam along with the [[Dee River (Queensland)|Dee River]] both flooded during the cyclone.<ref name=mtmorgan/>\n*'''John Warry''' - a man killed when he fell from his horse and drowned while attempting to drive cattle across Callide Creek near [[Goovigen]].<ref name=twodrowned/>\n\n===Injuries===\nMany non-fatal injuries were reported during the cyclone.<ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76178757 Cyclone victims and casualties], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  Many rescues also took place during and following the cyclone.<ref>(3 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/49932101 Ordeal of city in blackout], ''The Courier-Mail''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref> A family of seven was rescued by police after sheltering under their demolished house at Gavial Siding for two days without food.<ref>(5 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56896404/5484314 Rescue job by police], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Relief Fundraising==\nThe Rockhampton Cyclone Relief Fund was established soon after the cyclone, to assist victims in the [[City of Rockhampton]], [[Livingstone Shire]] and [[Fitzroy Shire]] areas.<ref>(10 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/76179152 Committees set up for relief of distress], ''The Central Queensland Herald''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  By 8 June 1949, a total of \u00a33162 had been raised for the fund.<ref name=end>(9 June 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56906755 End cyclone relief payments in fortnight, says mayor], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>   A total of 79 applications totalling of \u00a31466/5/10 in assistance had been authorised while another 225 applications from the relief fund were under consideration.<ref name=end/>\n\nGladstone also had a similar cyclone relief fund.<ref>(19 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/191845596 \u00a3100 gift for cyclone relief funds], ''[[Warwick Daily News]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>(26 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/117096654 Forest Hill CWA], ''Queensland Times''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nA variety show was held at the Palais Royal in Rockhampton on 6 April 1949 as a fundraising event, featuring well known Brisbane comedians Buster Fiddes and Mavis Monk.<ref>(6 April 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56899747 Variety show for cyclone relief], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  The show had a disappointing crowd with only 270 people attending the event.<ref>(7 April 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56899875 Cyclone relief benefit], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nFollowing the cyclone, discussions took place regarding how to improve warnings of an approaching cyclone. The Rockhampton Chamber of Commerce criticised the fact that no person in the city had been tasked with the responsibility of warning people of an incoming cyclone.<ref>(22 April 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/56901500 Cyclone warning responsibility], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThere were also calls in the press for homes, businesses and public property in northern and central areas of Queensland to be strengthened to better withstand tropical cyclones that crossed the coast into populated areas.<ref>(6 March 1949) [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/98290844 Grim lesson of cyclone: North must build stronger homes], ''[[The Sunday Mail (Brisbane)|The Sunday Mail]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe 1949 Central Queensland cyclone is still remembered by many residents in Rockhampton and Gladstone.<ref>(14 November 2007) [http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2007/10/24/2069363.htm Discover Central Queensland - Ambrose], [[ABC Capricornia]]. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref><ref>Spelitis, Helen (6 February 2009) [https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/late-start-to-cyclone-season-not-unusual/2535415 Cyclone season is running late, but may still hit hard - one died in Gladstone as 1949 cyclone hit town], ''[[The Observer (Gladstone)|The Observer]]''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>  However, until [[Cyclone Marcia]] struck Rockhampton in 2015, there had been a growing sense of complacency amongst others who had a misguided belief that the city would never be seriously affected by a cyclone.<ref>McKee, Christine (27 February 2015) [https://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/natures-fury-felt-across-centuries-cyclones-queens/2555313 Nature's fury felt across centuries across Queensland], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Charlie James Memorial Trophy has been awarded to local Rockhampton [[tennis]] players since 1960. It is named after Charles James who was killed during the cyclone.<ref>Kennedy, Alan (6 February 2009) [https://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/cup-serves-up-49th-tourney/164272 Cup serves up 49th tourney], ''The Morning Bulletin''. Retrieved 11 December 2018.</ref>\n\n2 March 2019 will mark the 70th anniversary of the 1949 Central Queensland cyclone.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1949 in Australia]]\n[[Category:1949 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:Central Queensland]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclones in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Jason Rees", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1949_Central_Queensland_cyclone"}
